{
  "query": "What are the benefits of planting new hedges and managing existing ones for butterfly and moth conservation on farmland?",
  "relevant_summary": "Planting new hedges and managing existing ones provides numerous benefits for butterfly and moth conservation on farmland. Studies in the UK, Ireland, and Canada have shown that established hedgerows support a higher species richness of butterflies and macro-moths compared to other farm habitats like beetle banks, crops, or pastures (3976). The abundance of butterflies and moths is also greater along hedgerows than in open fields or on grass margins (3976). The composition of the hedge is important, as planting species like gorse, oak, and blackthorn can support a higher number of arthropod species, including caterpillars, than the more commonly planted hawthorn (3976).\n\nThe management of existing hedgerows also plays a crucial role. Hedgerows with a more complex structure, such as those with trees, have a higher diversity of butterflies and moths (3975). Management practices like cutting hedgerows less frequently (every 2-3 years), cutting in autumn, or allowing for incremental growth can increase the abundance of butterflies, moths, and their caterpillars (3975). The height and shape of the hedge also matter; hedgerows kept between 1-2 meters tall in Italy and those with scalloped edges in Belgium have been found to support more butterflies and their eggs (3975). Laid or coppiced hedges in the UK also had a higher abundance of butterflies than unmanaged ones (3975). Furthermore, providing training and advice to landowners about agri-environment schemes has resulted in the management of large areas of farmland for the benefit of species like the marsh fritillary butterfly (3846).",
